Date: 14 Nov 2000 11:56:13 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Panafrican News Agency, 13 Nov 2000 [edited

South Africa Steps Up War Against Foot-And-Mouth Disease
------------------------------------------------------------
South Africa's veterinary authorities have ordered the cordoning-off of a
huge area to ensure that 3 million cloven-hoofed animals will be vaccinated
to prevent the further spread of foot-and-mouth disease in KwaZulu-Natal.
Up to now there has only been a 30-km control zone around the
Camperdown-Georgedale area where the disease broke out 2 months ago. But
the new area encompasses almost a third of the entire province.
The disease control centre in Pietermaritzburg said nobody would be allowed
to move any cloven-hoofed animal, any product of cloven-hoofed animals or
any kitchen refuse in or out of the zone, with immediate effect.
The directive will last until further notice. It said that branding to
ensure traceability would identify all vaccinated animals. "Surveillance
activities inside and outside the area will be intensified and broadened,"
it added.
The disease broke out on a pig farm at Camperdown 2 months ago and despite
hopes that it had been contained, new infections were discovered over the
past couple of weeks. So far almost 7000 animals have been put down since
the disease was first detected and 17 countries have imposed partial or
complete bans on the export of cloven-hoofed animals or products from South
Africa or KwaZulu-Natal.
Dr Kraai van Niekerk, Democratic Alliance Spokesman called on the Minister
of Agriculture and the government to institute a state of emergency in
order to control the disease. "This outbreak of foot and mouth is
everybody's problem and co-operation is needed to fight it. These efforts
will only be successful if the agriculture community is fully involved in
the efforts. "Internationally renowned experts should also be called in to
join scientists in taking over the fight against foot-and-mouth," he said.
