Source: The Times, 10 Nov 2000 [edited

Spain may be sued over giraffe deaths
---------------------------------------
The Spanish Government is facing legal action for damages after the death
of 2 giraffes on board a container ship bound for South Africa. Spain
refused to allow a wildlife consignment to enter its waters because of
fears about foot-and-mouth disease. The 2 giraffes died in their wooden
crates 7 days after the vessel left Malta. It is thought they may have
fallen over after becoming seasick and were trampled to death by other
giraffes in the crates.
They were among a consignment of 3 rhinos and 24 giraffes which left South
Africa on 5 Oct 2000 for the 3-week journey to Valencia. The surviving
animals have been at sea for more than a month and are not expected to
arrive [back in South Africa until 19 Nov 2000.
Global Wildlife Logistics, the Ladysmith company that handled the shipment,
said it had received a radio message from the ship's captain that the
giraffes had died on the way to Madagascar. [Presumably since leaving Malta.
They have been at sea for far too long," a spokesman said. "We hold the
Spanish Government responsible. We have taken on enormous costs to bring
the animals back. The alternative was to throw them in the sea."
The Spanish authorities turned back the animals because of a serious
outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease near the port city of Durban and after
claiming that blood tests showed that some of the animals may have been
carrying the deadly disease.
Jeff Richmond, managing director of Global Wildlife Logistics, said that
the Spanish fears were groundless and that they had ignored South African
veterinary certification that the animals were healthy. An appeal fund has
been set up to pay for the return of the animals.
[Byline: Michael Dynes
